STRATEGIC_REASONING: {'Compute a high-utility core set for me using value/effort intuition; start with very efficient low-effort items plus several large high-impact ones. Leave meaningful slack under LIMIT to make it easier to accommodate opponent unknown must-haves without immediately forcing painful swaps. Open with a concrete proposal and an argument highlighting slack and flexibility.'}
PROPOSAL: {'A87', 'A03', 'C00', 'B86', 'B41', 'A10', 'A71', 'C01'}
ARGUMENT: {'This set is comfortably within the shared effort LIMIT (leaves 591 effort of headroom) while covering A/B/C items.', 'The remaining headroom lets us add either one medium-effort item (like B32 or C54) or a couple smaller items if you have must-haves.', 'If you tell me your top 1–2 priority items to include, I can adjust while keeping total effort ≤ 3624.'}

STRATEGIC REASONING: {'I need to use the exact tag "STRATEGIC REASONING". I will restate a strong, flexible proposal that stays well under the limit (leaving slack) so the other player can add one medium item they care about. Keep the same set since it is feasible and high value for me, and include an ARGUMENT to justify flexibility.'}
PROPOSAL: {'A87', 'A03', 'C00', 'B86', 'B41', 'A10', 'A71', 'C01'}
ARGUMENT: {'This set stays within the shared effort LIMIT and leaves 591 effort of headroom for your must-have items.', 'With the remaining headroom, we can still add one medium-effort item (e.g., B32 or C54) or a couple small items without breaking the limit.', 'If you name 1–2 items you care most about, I can revise the bundle while keeping total effort ≤ 3624.'}

STRATEGIC_REASONING: {'Opponent offered a reasonable base bundle with 591 effort slack. I can likely get them to accept a superset (adding items can’t hurt if all importances are nonnegative). My highest-impact, low-effort additions that fit in 591 are A04 (121) and C17 (210); together 331 effort, huge utility gain for me while keeping all their chosen items. This is the safest improvement vs trying to swap out their big-effort items (A71/A10/C01), which they may value.'}
PROPOSAL: {'A87', 'A03', 'C00', 'B86', 'B41', 'A10', 'A71', 'C01', 'A04', 'C17'}
ARGUMENT: {'My top add-ins are A04 and C17.', 'They only consume 331 additional effort total, so the full set remains comfortably under the 3624 LIMIT.', 'This keeps your entire original bundle intact while adding two low-effort items, so it should be strictly better than the baseline proposal.'}

STRATEGIC REASONING: {'I should keep their entire proposed bundle (so they lose nothing) and use the remaining 591 effort headroom to add a couple items that matter a lot to me. Adding A04 (121 effort) and C17 (210 effort) uses only 331 more, keeping us under 3624, and is easier to accept than asking them to swap out any of their chosen high-effort items.'}
PROPOSAL: {'A87', 'A03', 'C00', 'B86', 'B41', 'A10', 'A71', 'C01', 'A04', 'C17'}
ARGUMENT: {'This keeps every item from your original bundle unchanged.', 'A04 + C17 add only 331 effort total, so we remain within the 3624 LIMIT.', 'Since nothing is removed, this should be an easy improvement over the baseline.'}

STRATEGIC_REASONING: {'Their proposal is feasible and improves on my baseline, but I can potentially do better for my objectives by using the remaining effort more “impactfully.” I will counterpropose a minimal-change swap: replace the two small add-ons (A04, C17) with one medium item (C54), keeping the original core unchanged. I will not REFUSE so their proposal remains available to accept later if they insist.'}
PROPOSAL: {'A87', 'A03', 'C00', 'B86', 'B41', 'A10', 'A71', 'C01', 'C54'}
ARGUMENT: {'This keeps the entire original core bundle unchanged and stays within the 3624 LIMIT (total effort 3616).', 'It swaps the two add-ons (A04 + C17) for a single item (C54) while keeping overall effort in the same range, and leaves a little slack (8).', 'If A04 or C17 are must-haves for you, say so and we can revert to your add-on version.'}

STRATEGIC REASONING: {'Resend my counterproposal using the exact required tag. Keep it close to their expanded bundle but swap their two add-ons for one alternative item, staying within the LIMIT. Emphasize feasibility and willingness to revert if their add-ons are must-haves.'}
